				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Agro, Engagement and KSing<a name="67967"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 24 04 9:36 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span> Quote:
<br />
 Alternatively, you kite Gore around waiting for your friends to show up and someone takes her - this is not kill stealing because you are not prepared to engage it.
<br />

<br />
  I can't say for sure in the eyes of a GM whether or not this would be considered KSing. Suppose you were kiting Gore waiting for friends and a group was trying to pull him from you. Can they prove you were not trying to solo it? You could agrue that you were mana draining it to make it easier to kill and this  would take a long time on Gore. Heck you could even do some damage so it was not at 100% health but keep it above 96% so it doesn't summon you. Could they prove you weren't actually pulling to a group on the other side of the zone? 
<br />

<br />
  I'm not judging whether pulling and holding a mob by kiting or mezzing it till help arrives is right or wrong. I'm just trying to show that the person who pulls it may still have rights to it even though the group is not ready to engage. 
<br />

<br />
  I have soloed mobs like Spirit of Radir that took over a half hour to kill but that doesn't give anyone the right to pull it from me just because it takes a long time and they don't think I can solo it.  In the case I can't solo a mob I pull then anyone else who wants it would have to still wait till either I die trying, zone, fade (that may be questionable) or tell them they can have it.
<br />

<br />
  
<br />
</span></td>
